\series bold
[First main result: full disclosure is not efficient]
\series default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted -484307115 1485958981


\backslash
fi 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The first main result of the paper is that full information disclosure
 is inefficient.
 Specifically, there is a strategy profile for the sellers that generates
 higher surplus for both buyers and sellers than in the market equilibrium
 under full disclosure.
 There are two components for this inefficiency: inefficiency on the buyer
 side of the market and inefficiency on the seller side of the market.
 The driving force for inefficiency on the buyer side is that the set of
 matches that create positive surplus for the sellers is distinct from the
 set of matches that create positive surplus for the buyers.
 Sellers do not internalize buyer surplus when they make decisions whether
 or not to accept the buyers' requests.
 Disclosing more information to sellers reduces the platform's ability to
 induce sellers to accept the efficient matches.
 The sellers will single out the matches that are valuable to them and reject
 other matches that are potentially valuable to the buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted -484307115 1486042609
