\series bold
[Inefficiency on the seller side; Seller coordination failure]
\series default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted -484307115 1485965595


\backslash
fi 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The inefficiency of full disclosure on the seller side of the market is
 perhaps more surprising since each individual seller in isolation clearly
 benefits from more information.
 The fact that sellers become worse off as a whole is a consequence of the
 seller coordination failure.
 In a market where sellers act independently, each seller keeps his schedule
 open by rejecting low-value matches in order to increase his individual
 chances of getting high-value matches.
 As a result, sellers spend significant time waiting for high-value matches.
 Collectively, this behavior is suboptimal because both low- and high-value
 matches have to be accepted in order to maximize the joint seller surplus.
 I attribute the source of the coordination failure to what I call the 
\emph on
cream-skimming externality
\emph default
: By rejecting a buyer, a seller remains available on the marketplace and
 attracts a fraction of subsequent buyers who otherwise would contact  other
 sellers.
 As a result, the other sellers face fewer valuable buyers and realize lower
 profits.
 The cream-skimming externality arises  when sellers have correlated preferences
 over buyers, have limited capacity for serving buyers and are forward-looking.
 The platform's policy of withholding of information reduces the sellers'
 ability to cream-skim and allays the externality.
 In the second part of the paper, I study how the information disclosure
 affects market outcomes and characterize the efficient disclosure policy.
 
