\change_deleted -484307115 1486064778
The optimal disclosure policy must balance three effects: the positive effect
 on the seller quality of the match and the negative static and dynamic
 effects on the match rate.
 First, the effect of disclosure on the match quality is straightforward.
 From a seller’s point of view, more information increases his set of attainable
 payoffs.
 Holding the match rate fixed, he benefits from more information about buyers.
 Second, information disclosure reduces the platform’s ability to induce
 sellers to accept buyers.
 A key observation is that the platform can increase a seller's expected
 marginal profit by limiting the information revealed to him.
 To see why, note that pooling marginally profitable buyers (which are rejected
 because the seller would prefer to wait for a better buyer) with inframarginal
 buyers (which are accepted) alters the seller's expected marginal profit.
 Ignoring dynamic effects, higher marginal profit induces sellers to accept
 more buyers, which leads to higher match rates.
 Third, making more information available to a seller increases returns
 on his search.
 Indeed, since acceptance precludes further search, the opportunity cost
 of accepting a given buyer is higher.
 As a result, sellers reject buyers more often, and the match rate goes
 down.
 This dynamic effect on the match rate exists only when sellers have limited
 capacity and are forward looking.
 The match-quality effect provides a motive for the platform to disclose
 information, while the match-rate effects provide a motive to limit information.
\change_inserted -484307115 1486064778
The optimal disclosure policy must balance three effects of information
 disclosure: the positive effect on the sellers’ match quality and the negative
 static and dynamic effects on the match rate.
 On the one hand, the effect of information disclosure on the match quality
 is straightforward.
 From a seller’s point of view, more information increases his set of attainable
 payoffs.
 Holding the match rate fixed, he benefits from more details about buyers.
 On the other hand, information disclosure reduces the platform’s ability
 to induce sellers to accept more matches.
 The effect on match rate has static and dynamic components.
 The static component is standard for the information disclosure literature,
 but the dynamic component is novel.
 To understand the static component, represent the seller’s problem as a
 tradeoff between quantity (acceptance rate) and profit (match quality).
 In the optimum, a seller chooses the acceptance rate such that the expected
 profit from the marginal buyer is zero.
 A key observation then is that the platform can increase the seller’s expected
 marginal profit by limiting the information revealed to him.
 To see why, note that pooling marginally profitable buyers (which are rejected
 because the seller would prefer to wait for a better buyer) with inframarginal
 buyers (which are accepted) alters the seller’s expected marginal profit.
 Ignoring dynamic effects, higher marginal profit induces sellers to accept
 more buyers, which leads to higher match rates.
 The dynamic effect of disclosure on match rate stems from the fact that
 making more information available to a seller increases his return on the
 search.
 Indeed, although releasing more information to a seller expands his set
 of attainable payoffs, it also increases his opportunity cost of accepting
 any given buyer—since acceptance precludes receiving further buyer requests.
 As a result, sellers reject buyers more often, and the match rate goes
 down.
 The dynamic effect on the match rate only exists when sellers have limited
 capacity and are forward-looking.
 The match-quality effect provides a motive for the platform to disclose
 information, while the match-rate effects provide a motive to withhold
 information.

