\series bold
[The problem of optimal disclosure is non-trivial in the general case]
\series default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted -484307115 1486062480


\backslash
fi 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The question of finding an optimal disclosure policy is a non-trivial problem,
 and there are three main challenges in analyzing it.
 First, I do not restrict the class of disclosure policies in any way, that
 is I allow for arbitrary mappings from buyer characteristics to signals
 sent to sellers.
 This makes the problem multi-dimensional.
 Second, the seller preferences might have unobserved heterogeneity.
 Finally, the sellers are forward-looking, which as it turns out, prevents
 me from using the standard approaches in the literature on information
 disclosure.
 In the third point lies the main technical contribution of the paper.
 When sellers are forward-looking, the information disclosure policy determines
 not only the seller’s stage payoff but also his continuation value.
 In turn, continuation value depends on the distribution of future expected
 payoffs.
 As a result, a seller’s decision to accept depends not only on the posterior
 mean of the current buyer type—which is a standard feature in the existing
 models—but on the entire signaling structure.
 In this situation, the concavification approach of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KG11"

\end_inset

 and the linear programming approach of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kol15"

\end_inset

 are unsuitable for the analysis of this problem.
 My approach consists of three steps.
 First, I represent signaling structures as a particular class of convex
 functions.
 Second, I use the calculus of variations to find the first-order conditions
 of optimality.
 Third, I use this first order necessary condition on convex functions to
 back out the optimal information policy (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:main-lemma"

\end_inset

).
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

