When sellers are unobservably heterogeneous, the optimal disclosure policy
 is finer than in the case of identical sellers.
 With heterogeneous sellers, the effect of information disclosure on match
 quality is stronger, but there are important subtleties.
 Coarse disclosure tailored to increase one seller’s acceptance rate can
 drive another seller’s average profit below zero and violate his individual
 rationality constraint.
 If any coarsening is optimal in this case, the degree of coarsening is
 now not obvious.
 The optimal policy should accommodate the possibly opposite reactions of
 different sellers to disclosure and will depend on the shape of the seller
 type distribution.
